actions.text: Corporate personhood was established mainly through Supreme Court rulings, starting with the late 19th century's Santa Clara County case.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The Santa Clara case involved local government and Southern Pacific Railroad, focusing on equal protection rights.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The case is Santa Clara County v. Southern Pacific Railroad, with Chief Justice Waite leading a more activist court.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The Santa Clara County v. Southern Pacific Railroad case was decided in 1886.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Corporate personhood has expanded, giving companies greater legal rights, like free speech in campaigns.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Corporations can avoid personal liability, while individuals face legal consequences for their actions.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Corporations can limit their financial risk; owners typically arent personally liable for business debts.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Corporations can donate unlimited money in politics, while people face donation limits and ethical scrutiny.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Proponents argue corporate personhood protects free speech and encourages economic growth by allowing businesses to participate in democracy.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Im always learning! Sometimes I miss the mark, but I'm here to improve.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: A corporation is defined as a legal entity that can own assets, enter contracts, and sue or be sued.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: To create a corporation, file articles of incorporation with your state and define its structure and purpose.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Yes, interest groups can be corporations if they organize for a common cause or goal.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Federalism means states can set unique corporation laws, leading to different rights and regulations across the country.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The Supreme Court can review state laws if they violate federal constitutional rights related to corporate personhood.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Corporations enjoy First Amendment rights, affecting political donations and advertising, reshaping federal election dynamics.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The Supreme Court had a majority of justices appointed by Republican presidents in 1886.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The majority in Citizens United were mostly appointed by Republican presidents, and the case was decided in 2010.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Many democracies recognize corporate personhood, but the U.S. offers corporations unusually extensive legal rights.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Yeah, Walmarts not a person like you and me, but it has similar rights legally!
